e creative and economic opportunities that have sprung up around them—or that they forged—during Japan’s astonishingly fast modernization. She shows that modernist Japanese composers have not bought into the high modernist concept of the autonomous artist, instead remaining connected to the people. Articulating Japanese modernism in this way, Wade tells a larger story of international musical life, of the spaces in which tradition and modernity are able to meet and, ultimately, where modernity itself has been made.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aComposerszJapan. 0aMusiczJapanxWestern influences. 0aMusiczJapany20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  ajapan, composition, composer, music, audio, modern, contemporary, major, college, university, textbook, asia, asian, eastern, orchestra, artist, instrumental, musician, performance, 19th century, culture, cultural, global, cosmopolitan, society, social studies, academic, scholarly, research, economics, modernization, technology, change, tradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226085494423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226085494/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles